    "summary": "Laurens Landeweerd (philosopher) is lecturer (UD1) and researcher at the Department of Philosophy and Science studies with the teaching and research assignment \u2018reflection on science and technology\u2019. He also works as a coach for iArts Maastricht and chairman of the programme board of Filosofie Oost-West. \n\nFrom 20176 tot 2018 he was part time senior researcher at Oslo and Akershus University. \n\nLandeweerd studies metaphysics and epistemology (Amsterdam) as well as the philosophy of art and culture (Maastricht&Amsterdam). He was involved in various projects for the European Commission on the ethical, legal and social aspects of biotechnology. \n\nLandeweerd was involved in several Dutch projects on ethics and governance of industrial biotechnology. He was acting coordinator for the FP7 SynthEthics project and researcher for 9 further European projects on ethics and governance of science and technology (RRI/ELSI), on topics such as eugenics, human enhancement, bioethics, industrial biotechnology, biofuels and the biobased society.\n\nFrom 2007, he worked as researcher and project supervisor at TU Delft\u2019s department of Biotechnology and Society, a.o. for the project Global Normative Frameworks for Sustainability.  His main research interest can be circumscribed as \u2018applied metaphysics\u2019: an investigation of social issues of science and technology on the basis of concept analysis and (normative) philosophical theory.\n\nLandeweerd was a junior researcher and later general researcher at the department of Health Ethics and Philosophy (now Health, Ethics and Society) at Maastricht University (2002-2007), writing a thesis on eugenics (\u2018Reconstructing the Self\u2019) whilst also involved in several European research and PhD education projects. Prior. Landeweerd worked on a complete revision of a Dutch history of philosophy (25 Eeuwen (Westerse) Filosofie; 2001-2002). Landeweerd studied Philosophy at the University of Amsterdam and Culture & Science at Maastricht University (1994-2000).",
